<TEXT>
the call by saddam hussein for arab forces 
to rise up to protect islam is being seriously heeded in egypt but 
thousands of eager young egyptians are signing up to fight the 
iraqi president not his enemies 
on monday as they have for days crowds of university 
graduates civil servants and unemployed youth milled outside the 
embassies of saudi arabia the united arab emirates and kuwait in 
hopes of enlisting in those oilrich countries armies kuwait has 
been occupied since aug 2 by iraqi forces 
some said dreams of big money as mercenaries were alluring 
however most emphasized their goals were to save islams holiest 
shrines in mecca and medina from desecration either by iraqis or by 
westerners fighting to repel what some believe is an imminent iraqi 
invasion of saudi arabia 
a saudi official said 4000 men had registered since saturday 
for duty 
if mecca falls were finished said ashraf ahmed a 
25yearold schoolteacher i want to go fight because the iraqis 
are bad people because we want to free our brothers there in 
kuwait and because we want to defend the islamic holy places 
ahmed was among at least 200 men overflowing into the street 
beside the saudi embassy filling out papers and stuffing them 
through a small window to an embassy employee 
the scene was being repeated blocks away at the embassy of the 
united arab emirates the uae and saudi arabia are among persian 
gulf countries who asked other arabs for help to defend themselves 
against a possible iraqi incursion 
egypt morocco and syria are among those countries committing 
troops in line with a resolution adopted by 12 states at an arab 
summit friday the resolution also supported saudi arabias request 
for us military help which has led to deployment of a 
multinational force near its 500mile border with iraq 
as the summit was going on saddam issued a statement urging 
arabs to attack western forces in the gulf region he also said the 
saudi ruling family should be overthrown to protect and rescue 
the shrines of islam in the kingdom 
the enlistment queues at the saudi uae and kuwait embassies 
appeared to have formed spontaneously 
the saudi embassy official who spoke of 4000 registrants said 
the embassy had not advertised for volunteers they just came on 
their own he said 
a letter is all that is needed including a volunteers name 
age profession military experience and willingness to join the 
armed forces 
the saudi official who spoke on condition of anonymity said he 
has no idea what will become of the offers 
we will later transfer all these forms to the egyptian 
government he said some of the volunteers ask me about 
payment but i tell them we havent heard of that at all 
the volunteers were discussing figures of 2600 saudi riyals per 
month about 695 monthly at current conversion rates to 10000 
riyals or 2674 for the whole mission 
egypts latest per capita income is about 670 annually 
one of the volunteers said he would be surprised if they were 
not rewarded for their service said salem sayed outside the 
kuwaiti embassy there will probably be some kind of appreciation 
for standing by them 
about 3000 egyptian soldiers have arrived in saudi arabia a 
significant contribution by an arab country but small compared to 
the estimated 50000 us forces scheduled to be sent there 
another 1000 egyptian troops are expected soon in saudi arabia 
</TEXT>
