<TEXT>
experts say moral and political considerations would keep the 
united states from retaliating in kind to a chemical weapons strike 
by iraq but there is another constraint the weapons would 
accomplish little 
much of the us arsenal of poison gas weapons is old and 
defective what could be used is designed for a closequarters 
fight in european fields and forests not the hot open expanses of 
the desert moreover nearly half the 30000 tons of us chemical 
agents sits in storage tanks in arkansas indiana and other states 
what chemicals the united states could get there would be in 
artillery shells and that doesnt figure into the kind of response 
wed want to make said gordon burck a washington consultant and 
former director of studies on chemical and biological warfare at 
the federation of american scientists 
the united states and other powers pledged in an international 
pact during the 1970s not to be the first to use chemical weapons 
the use of chemical weapons in war were banned under the geneva 
conventions after world war i 
experts like burck agree there is little chance us forces 
would ever use chemical weapons in response to an iraqi attack the 
nation and its allies could not abide their use the united states 
would lose whatever moral high ground it now has in the arab world 
following iraqs invasion of kuwait 
it would put the president on the same moral plane as iraq 
president saddam hussein in the eyes of people who havent made up 
their mind on the issue said matthew meselson a harvard 
biochemist who has advised arms control negotiators since 1963 
although this country has not used lethal chemical agents since 
world war i large quantities of tear gas known as cs were used 
during the vietnam war 
they shipped 11 million pounds of it in 155mm shells and 
500pound bombs said meselson the purpose was to force men 
out of protective cover so they could come into the line of fire 
it was called a force multiplier but it didnt multiply the 
force much it wasnt very successful 
the united states arsenal of lethal chemicals includes mustard 
gas which can burn the skin and lungs the lethal nerve gas known 
as ga or sarin and vx a more deadly nerve agent that can kill 
after limited contact to the skin 
the weapons and chemicals are kept in alabama arkansas 
colorado indiana kentucky maryland oregon and tooele utah 
where 40 percent of the us arsenal is stored 
chemical artillery shells kept in europe are slated to be moved 
to johnston atoll in the pacific later this year to be destroyed 
brad roberts a chemical arms expert at washingtons center for 
strategic and international studies said these weapons were 
stockpiled over the years as a deterrent in any european land war 
with the soviet union 
but in the mid1980s a presidential commission reported that 
only 11 percent to 28 percent of the us stockpile had any 
military application half the stockpile is simply chemicals stored 
in bulk 
most of the chemical bombs rockets and land mines produced 
from world war ii until 1969 are outdated and unreliable roberts 
said much of the chemical artillery shells are for 105mm cannon 
which is now in limited use 
the artillery weapons that remain available would have little 
military value in any conflict envisioned in the middle east 
the war we seem to be looking at is not of artillery duels or 
ground attacks as we envisioned in europe but of air 
superiority said roberts the only kinds of these weapons that 
could be used would be air delivered bombs and we dont have any 
the military and political limitations of chemical warfare 
raised in the iraq crisis and the new strategic situation in europe 
are likely to renew debate over eliminating us chemical weapons 
entirely 
if they couldnt use them in this scenario where could they 
use it asked burck we made a gross mistake in past years and 
made things we probably didnt need we may reevaluate keeping any 
stockpiles at all 
</TEXT>
