<TEXT>
rock singer don henley and other luminaries from 
music and politics launched an effort monday to preserve walden 
pond by buying some adjoining land slated for development 
the walden woods project is buying a 25acre stretch of the 
woodland made famous by literary recluse henry david thoreau to 
forestall plans for a 139unit condominium 
the project along with a group called the trust for public 
land also is negotiating to acquire another section of woods 700 
yards from the pond which is scheduled to be an office park 
henley formerly of the eagles rock group founded the walden 
woods project and shares the chairmanship with us sen paul 
tsongas and michael kennedy son of the late sen robert kennedy 
and president of the citizens energy corp 
the group announced agreements with the state and private 
developers to conserve land around the pond where thoreau built an 
cabin and lived for two years and also promoted an effort to 
create affordable housing in nearby concord 
henley was joined by singers bonnie raitt arlo guthrie aimee 
mann and members of the band boston 
the group is using a 100000 grant from hearst magazines for a 
down payment on the proposed condominium site 
hearst officials said all advertising revenues from the first 
issue of their new publication countryside will be donated to 
eight land trust programs around the country 
about 500000 people visit walden pond every year and for many 
of them its the closest they come to a natural wilderness 
experience said peter forbes new england regional director for 
the trust for public land 
walden pond is a 62acre body of water in a 333acre state 
reservation on the edge of concord an affluent town of 12500 
about 20 miles from boston 
the pond is far less pastoral than described in walden 
thoreaus 1854 meditation on solitude and the wilderness it lies 
less than a hundred yards from a highway and is next to a garbage 
dump 
henley organized the efforts after seeing a tv report earlier 
this year about the proposed developments near walden pond 
</TEXT>
