<TEXT>
president bush has asked japan to increase its aid 
to middle eastern nations affected by the persian gulf crisis 
foreign ministry officials said today 
the foreign ministry did not specify which nations were 
considered for increased aid egypt jordan and turkey are among 
japanese aid recipients affected by the increaed tensions following 
iraqs invasion of kuwait on aug 2 
bush telephoned kaifu monday night us time which was this 
morning in japan and asked japan to boost its support of countries 
involved in the crisis said a foreign ministry official speaking 
on condition of anonymity 
kaifu was quoted as replying that japan was studying how it 
could cooperate with the international effort to restore peace and 
stability in the region and he would consider expanding support 
for nations affected by the crisis 
japan is debating how to increase its backing for the 
international effort to make iraq withdraw its invaders from 
kuwait and kaifu on monday postponed a trip to five middle eastern 
countries in order to concentrate on the gulf crisis 
japans constitution forbids the use of force to resolve 
international disputes and the country could not send military 
units to join the usled multinational force that is quarantining 
trade with iraq 
in 1987 confronted with similar demands from its western 
partners to aid the effort against iraqi and iranian attacks on oil 
tankers in the gulf japan eventually gave indirect financial help 
tokyo financed a navigation system to keep track of ships in the 
gulf gave jordan loans and grants worth about 550 million and a 
credit line of 300 million and increased the money it paid to 
support us troops based in japan 
but the japanese government decided against sending a 
minesweeper to the gulf as other countries did because of the 
constitutional ban on sending troops into action overseas 
a high foreign ministry official told reporters monday that 
japan is determined to decide on concrete measures to help in 
the gulf crisis makoto watanabe director of the ministrys middle 
eastern affairs bureau said the government will examine all 
possible measures while observing the provisions of the 
constitution 
japan has agreed to a full trade embargo on iraq and kuwait 
which were supplying 112 percent of japans oil in the first half 
of 1990 
turkey borders iraq and has shut down iraqs parallel pipelines 
egyptian president hosni mubarak convened an arab league meeting 
last week that condemned iraqs invasion of kuwait and called for 
an arab force to be sent to saudi arabia the first arab troops to 
arrive there were egyptians 
</TEXT>
