<TEXT>
once again in the persian gulf as in korea 
and the cuban missile crisis an administration is seeking soft 
words for harsh actions 
president bush vows a total bar to iraqi shipping but avoids 
calling it a blockade 
us warplanes are conducting fighter missions over the gulf 
but the president says the united states is not at war 
more than 3000 americans are trapped in kuwait and iraq but 
nobody will call them hostages 
the semantic distinctions have legal as well as political 
reasons behind them experts say but they also suggest it is wise 
to pay attention to what the administration does not just what it 
says 
it does seem to be functionally a limited naval blockade 
said w thomas mallison professor emeritus of law at george 
washington university and a specialist in the law of armed conflict 
if you are stopping ships it sounds suspiciously like a 
blockade doesnt it said si hayakawa the former california 
senator who is the author of widely used books on semantics 
the administration avoids calling it a blockade because the term 
can be interpreted as meaning an act of war 
lets not use the word blockade secretary of state james a 
baker iii said in a television interview sunday lets just say 
we have the legal basis for interdicting these things 
bush at his home in kennebunkport maine said no point 
getting into all these semantics the main thing is to stop the oil 
from coming out of there and that is what were going to do 
asked whether food shipments to iraq would also be blocked the 
president replied just watch everything 
a spokesman for australias foreign ministry announcing monday 
that his government will join the action used the term 
blockade and said the aim was to prevent any supplies from 
going into or out of iraq 
mallison as a retired naval officer worked with navy lawyers 
on the 1962 quarantine of soviet vessels carrying offensive 
missiles to cuba the soviets at first challenged the blockade but 
later diverted their ships 
mallison said the word blockade was avoided because it 
conjured up pictures of the us and british blockades of 
world war ii which said in effect to the axis enemy that you cant 
use the oceans 
perhaps the interdiction terminology is used here as it was in 
the cuban situation to indicate that there are limitations on it 
he said 
in his televised address before flying to kennebunkport last 
week bush assured the nation that were not in a war in the 
persian gulf 
at the moment i guess were not said mallison 
hayakawa agreed saying that at this time it is something 
very much short of a war 
the united states has committed 50000 troops to the region and 
warplanes from the carrier uss independence have been conducting 
fighter missions over the gulf for several hours a night since a 
few days after iraqs armed takeover of kuwait on aug 2 
in 1950 president truman used the phrase police action to 
describe the dispatch of united nations troops most of them 
american to korea before the war ended three years later about 
580000 un and south korean troops and 16 million north korean 
and chinese fighting men were killed or wounded 
you could again call it korea a limited war functionally 
mallison said 
he said the laws of armed conflict such as those governing 
treatment of prisoners of war go into effect under the geneva 
convention whatever label you put on it 
the state department said monday that about 500 americans have 
quietly slipped out of kuwait since the iraqi invasion 
circumventing iraqi efforts to detain them this leaves about 2500 
in kuwait and 500 to 600 in iraq 
the administration has refused to call them hostages 
hostages frequently are associated with some kind of a demand 
and the iraq government in spite of having made various demands 
hasnt linked any of them to us or other western personnel 
said mallison 
of course in view of what happened to jimmy carter and the 
great anguish over the embassy captives in iran there is fear also 
of political fallout domestically if you call them hostages he 
said 
former president carter was defeated for reelection in 1980 
after prolonged efforts which succeeded on ronald reagans 
inauguration day to free 52 americans held hostage in tehran 
bush responding to a question in kennebunkport refused to 
describe the detention of americans by the iraqis as a hostage 
situation 
state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler has described the 
americans as sequestered 
</TEXT>
