east german workers drove tractors combines 
and lumber trucks into west berlin today demanding help from east 
and west german governments for their struggling farms and forest 
industry 
farmers and lumber workers have been among the hardest hit by 
the massive changes sweeping east germany theyre seeking higher 
wages and job security 
imported products from the west have cut demand for east german 
items inefficiency is another bone of contention 
we have such old machines some of them made before the war 
said 20yearold alexander witt during the protest at the historic 
reichstag building 
were supposed to compete in a capitalist system but its 
hard with such old machines that often break down and need repairs 
and maintenance he continued 
reflecting on the complexities that still pervade the east 
german economy witt said he was not a farmer but rather an 
expert for plant production his job preparing the soil 
sowing and harvesting 
witt from schoenefeld outside berlin was one of about 70 
workers who had gathered by late morning in front of the reichstag 
the massive building to become the parliament of a united germany 
the protesters drove there in more than 35 farm and forestry 
vehicles with dozens more expected by the afternoon 
all wore rough work clothes often flecked with dirt 
some took the opportunity to sell their products which have 
been unable to compete with western goods flooding east germany 
if we dont sell we cant keep working shouted a burly 
farm worker as he sold potatoes and peppers 
the banner on the side of his truck read we cant go on like 
this 
east germanys agricultural sector driven by four decades by 
communist governments before the inauguration of a noncommunist 
freemarket administration this year is collapsing under the 
weight of competition about half of the farms are technically 
bankrupt economists say 
that means hard times for the 800000 farmers who till the 
countrys sovietstyle collectives they face an uncertain feature 
when the two germanys merge later this year 
most of the workers taking part in todays protest said they 
earned about 500 to 550 a month in base pay adding they needed 
overtime to survive 
forest workers are having similarly difficult times 
the sawmills wont take our wood any more said lumber truck 
driver edwin braun they take wood from bavaria and the soviet 
union but not ours 
and our wood is still cheaper it just doesnt make any 
sense said braun from the town of neustrelitz about 60 miles 
north of berlin 
banners on the huge vehicles demanded support from the west 
german and east german governments 
one predicted a hot autumn if east germanys agricultural 
business continues its dangerous plunge 
