<TEXT>
a tentative settlement has been reached in a 
strike at a general motors corp parts plant but the walkout 
highlighted the giant automakers vulnerability to local labor 
problems 
the 2800 united auto workers union members at the ac rochester 
west parts plant in flint walked off their jobs wednesday in what 
was billed as a local dispute over health and safety and other 
matters 
by monday parts shortages created by the strike forced the 
shutdown of four assembly plants and partial closings of four 
component factories idling about 11500 employees 
a tentative agreement was reached monday afternoon and union 
members were to vote on it this afternoon spokesman john maciarz 
said gm hoped the strikers would return to work by wednesday making 
fuel tanks and grilles for a variety of gm cars and trucks 
but it will take longer for assembly plant workers to get back 
to their jobs since the parts pipelines to those plants have been 
dried up maciarz said 
the rippling effect of the parts plant strike is a symptom of a 
justintime delivery system embraced by automakers it calls 
for parts to be delivered to assembly plants sometimes just hours 
before they are needed on assembly lines 
the strike came as the uaw was negotiating threeyear contracts 
with gm ford motor co and chrysler corp covering more than 
450000 workers current uaw agreements with the big three expire 
sept 14 
labor experts said monday that the strike may indicate that uaw 
leaders want gm to be the company the union chooses to bargain with 
first to set the pattern for contracts at the other automakers 
dale brickner of michigan state universitys school of labor and 
industrial relations said it was significant that the international 
union didnt press the local at the parts plant not to strike in 
order to avoid friction at the national negotiations 
the important point is the fact that the international hasnt 
clamped down saying no you cant do this because of 
negotiations going on brickner said 
by monday afternoon gm shut down truck assembly plants in 
moraine ohio shreveport la and pontiac and a car plant in 
flint other car plants near pontiac and in wentzville mo 
outside st louis were in danger of closure 
about 1000 other workers were laid off when production was cut 
at component plants in flint kokomo ind and warren ohio 
