<TEXT>
an environmental group said it would not 
oppose plans to conduct the first field test of a genetically 
engineered vaccine on wildlife in the united states 
the virginia department of health announced monday that a 10day 
test of a rabies vaccine will begin aug 20 it will be tested on 
parramore island an uninhabited barrier island about 4 miles off 
the coast of virginia 
the national wildlife federation which had initially fought 
plans to conduct tests because of safety concerns will not object 
to the field test according to margaret mellon a molecular 
biologist and lawyer for the group 
the tests will be done by the wistar institute of philadelphia 
which began work on the vaccine in 1982 wistar is a nonprofit 
independent biomedical research center 
ms mellon said the group was appalled by the way us 
department of agriculture officials were so quick to support 
wistars plans but said refinements in the plans made the 
federation more comfortable with the project 
the usda the state of virginia and the nature conservancy a 
nonprofit organization that owns the sevenmile long island 
approved the field test the conservancy consented to the project 
monday after coming to an agreement with wistar over several 
concerns including legal responsibility 
we realized that this island was really one of the few if not 
only places the test could be done said a conservancy 
spokeswoman holley darden 
the vaccine was developed to combat the problem of rabid 
raccoons which have reached epidemic levels in the midatlantic 
states in recent years said dr warren cheston wistars associate 
director 
so far this year 127 rabies cases have been reported in 
virginia while pennsylvania has documented 376 cases according to 
state health authorities 
during the field test scientists will scatter bait laden with 
the vaccine over the island researchers will then spend the next 
year tracking the animals and testing their blood to see if they 
have developed antibodies to the rabies virus 
ms darden said the islands raccoon population which numbers 
about 400 has not been previously exposed to rabies she said the 
wistar institute would follow guidelines to prevent island animals 
from escaping to the mainland 
the island will be offlimits to the public and monitored by the 
virginia department of game and inland fisheries 
the vaccine could be commercially available in as few as five 
years if the trial goes well and further tests are also successful 
according to dr david espeseth of the usda 
scientists developed the vaccine by inserting a gene from the 
rabies virus into the live vaccinia virus an organism used to 
develop vaccines against smallpox and other diseases the vaccine 
cannot spread the disease because it does not use the parts of the 
virus that cause rabies according to cheston 
more than 40 species of laboratory animals injected with the 
altered virus have shown immunity to rabies he said 
</TEXT>
