<TEXT>
iraqi president saddam hussein has 
systematically and ruthlessly eliminated dissent since he took 
power 11 years ago the economic siege of iraq likely will bring 
new hardship to his people but its open to question whether this 
will trigger serious opposition to his rule 
a few weeks before he sent his troops into kuwait on aug 2 
saddam arrested more than 40 senior military commanders in the 
latest of his periodic purges of men he suspected could challenge 
him iraqi dissident sources say 
generals who became too popular during the 198088 war with iran 
have disappeared fate unknown others died in a series of 
helicopter and auto accidents they included saddams cousin adnan 
khairallah who was the defense minister 
whether the latest reported purge was linked to saddams 
invasion plans is not clear but dissidents from various factions 
were reporting for some time before the arrests that there was 
discontent in the upper echelons of the military 
saddam 54 is the absolute ruler of iraq and its 16 million 
people he operates through the nineman revolutionary command 
council and the baath party which has been in power since a 1968 
coup after years as vice president and the real power in the 
ruling baath arab socialist party saddam shunted aside president 
ahmad hasan albakr to take over the presidency 
saddam has packed key positions with his relatives by blood or 
marriage they answer to him alone 
he is chairman of the command council and is also prime 
minister he has a handful of longtime aides such as first deputy 
prime minister taha yassin ramadan who is considered his 
secondincommand 
another important figure is tariq aziz the only christian in 
his 24man cabinet he is a deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister and saddams main adviser on foreign policy both are 
members of the command council 
but saddam is believed to wield almost total power 
he is a member of the minority sunni moslem sect some 55 
percent of iraqis are shiite moslems like most of irans 55 
million people 
iraq is a wellorganized police state and its government is 
one of the most brutal and repressive regimes in power today 
with the exception of freedom of worship the iraqi government 
ruthlessly suppresses even the smallest gesture of dissent the 
usbased middle east watch human rights group said in a recent 
report 
saddam controls iraqs 1 millionstrong armed forces and the 
countrys security and intelligence apparatus his intelligence 
services have hunted down and killed leading dissidents living 
abroad 
iraqis are encouraged to inform on their neighbors during the 
iraniraq war saddam publicly decorated fathers who turned in 
deserter sons 
publicly insulting saddam is a capital offense and sources in 
baghdad said some iraqis who made jokes about saddam had their 
tongues ripped out 
after the war against iran saddam announced a package of 
reforms including a multiparty system press freedom and 
presidential elections 
diplomats however said the changes were little more than 
cosmetic to keep iraqis acquiescent that belief was underlined 
when the compliant parliament last month called for saddam to be 
named president for life without any elections 
diplomats now expect saddam to shelve the promised reforms 
citing the crisis that he triggered 
the un sanctions against iraq are the toughest ever imposed by 
the world body and are expected to be felt quickly saddam on 
sunday called on iraqis to tighten their belts for what are certain 
to be difficult days ahead 
how long it might take for discontent to emerge is hard to say 
iraqis withstood hardship and shortages during the war with iran 
but the ceasefire raised expectations of better days 
iraqs official media daily churn out slogans hailing saddam as 
the new saladin the 12th century moslem warrior who defeated the 
crusaders and recaptured jerusalem the reports make no mention of 
dissent 
the reference to saladin is ironic saladin was a kurd and his 
descendants are among the tough mountain people who have been 
waging a fierce war for independence against the baghdad regime 
in march 1988 iraqi warplanes dropped poison gas bombs on the 
kurdish town of halabja killing some 5000 civilians western 
reporters who reached the town reported seeing hundreds of men 
women and children dead 
after the fighting with iran stopped saddam launched a major 
campaign against the kurds again reportedly using chemical weapons 
saddams other oppponents include the iranbacked addawa 
islami or islamic call a shiite fundamentalist movement that has 
assassinated scores of iraqi diplomats and senior officials 
hundreds of members along with their entire families have been 
reported executed 
