<TEXT>
president bush pressured japan on tuesday to do 
its utmost and increase its participation in international 
efforts to punish iraq for invading kuwait 
japanese officials said they were debating what tokyo should do 
because of a constitutional ban on overseas military activities 
the ban stems from japans defeat by the united states in world war 
ii and the postwar occupation of japan by us forces 
it was the third time bush and prime minister toshiki kaifu had 
conferred by telephone about the middle east crisis since the aug 
2 invasion 
a call from bush two days after the invasion helped speed 
japans decision to announce economic sanctions kaifu then called 
the us president to report japans action 
in the latest phone call bush told kaifu he hopes japan will 
do its utmost including providing support to middle east 
countries that have sacrificed a great deal following the 
invasion the foreign ministry said 
kaifu responded that japan is considering how it can cooperate 
effectively according to a ministry official we are 
evaluating what sort of cooperation is most suitable for japan 
he said speaking on condition of anonymity 
bush did not specify what contributions japan should make but 
his request for maximum efforts probably includes support for the 
usled multinational force that is blocking iraqi shipping in the 
persian gulf region said the ministry official 
japans postwar constitution forbids the use of force to resolve 
international disputes defense agency officials say the country 
cannot by law send military units to join the multinational force 
as a result japan does not have any idea what to do beyond 
joining in the economic sanctions that have already been decided 
upon the nationally circulated asahi shimbun said in an 
editorial tuesday 
tokyos sanctions include a trade embargo on iraq and kuwait 
which together supplied 112 percent of japans oil this year 
japans inability to decide on additional actions contributed to 
kaifus decision monday to postpone a planned visit this week to 
the middle east news reports said 
advisers worried that if kaifu made the trip without announcing 
new actions it would give the impression japan was not doing its 
share to help resolve the crisis political aides said 
japan found itself in a similar situation in 1987 when the west 
demanded it aid in the effort against iraqi and iranian attacks on 
oil tankers in the persian gulf japan eventually financed a 
navigation system to keep track of ships in the gulf it also gave 
jordan loans and grants worth about 550 million and a credit line 
of 300 million and increased the money it paid to support us 
troops based in japan 
the japanese government decided against sending a minesweeper to 
the gulf as other countries did at that time because of its ban 
on military action overseas 
a foreign ministry official said monday that japan was 
determined to decide on concrete measures to help in the 
crisis makoto watanabe director of the ministrys middle eastern 
affairs bureau said the government will examine all possible 
measures while observing the provisions of the constitution 
in this rapidly changing world japan will be forced to make 
decisions on its own more frequently the nationally circulated 
yomiuri shimbun said in an editorial tuesday it is now the time 
for the ruling liberal democratic party and the opposition parties 
to start discussions to decide what japan can and cannot do 
