<TEXT>
retail sales were virtually flat in july 
edging up just 01 percent the government said tuesday and 
analysts predicted consumers will cut back spending even further 
because of rising oil prices 
the commerce department said sales rose a seasonally adjusted 
1495 billion last month up just 132 million from june 
nevertheless some economists were encouraged by upward 
revisions showing stronger sales in may and june than previously 
had been reported 
when you combine july with a restatement of more momentum in 
the prior months youve got a consumer hinting at a firming of 
demand as the second half of the year got under way said steven 
s roach senior economist at morgan stanley amp co 
but that data has been rendered obsolete for now by the 
iraqi invasion of kuwait and the resulting surge in oil prices 
roach and other analysts added 
if the price of oil remains about 25 a barrel the average 
american household will pay 260 more per year roach said 
that obviously will put a crimp in consumer buying 
the impact will have to be negative agreed lea tyler 
senior economist with the wefa group in bala cynwyd pa the 
question is how big 
consumer spending accounts for twothirds of the nations 
economic activity and has fueled much of the economic growth since 
the last recession ended in 1982 retail sales themselves represent 
about half of overall consumer spending 
in its revisions the commerce department said june sales jumped 
a strong 11 percent rather than the 05 percent gain it reported 
last month at the same time it said may sales declined just 01 
percent rather than the 07 percent first believed 
the adjustment in the may figure combined with declines in 
april and march still meant sales had fallen for three consecutive 
months the first time that had happened since the recession year 
of 1981 
sales of durable goods bigticket items expected to last more 
than three years rose 03 percent in july following a 04 percent 
gain the previous month building materials were up 39 percent 
while furniture and other household furnishing sales rose 25 
percent 
but a 06 percent tumble in automobile sales wiped out a 06 
percent advance in june weakness in auto sales has been a major 
factor contributing to the overall sluggishness of consumer 
spending this year 
excluding autos retail sales were up 03 percent 
nondurable goods sales were unchanged following a 15 percent 
gain in june 
department store sales posted a 08 percent advance after a 
revised 35 percent increase the previous month june department 
store sales first were reported to have risen 28 percent grocery 
store sales were up 04 percent while drug store sales climbed 06 
percent 
but sales fell in three nondurable sectors gasoline station 
purchases were off 03 percent clothing sales were down 09 
percent and sales at restaurants and bars fell 04 percent 
