<TEXT>
united press international will lay off 31 
employees transfer others and leave some small news bureaus with 
no staff as part of a series of organizational changes the news 
agency said tuesday 
the washingtonbased wire service is also negotiating to 
purchase the use of the news report of states news service another 
washingtonbased news organization as part of a joint venture 
intended to supplement its own coverage of the federal government 
a upi spokesman said 
the spokesman milt capps said four regional reporters who had 
been tailoring upi reports of federal news for individual states 
and regions will be assigned other duties 
he said upis coverage on capitol hill will not otherwise be 
affected 
capps said the layoffs involve 16 fulltime employees and 15 
probationary staff members in upi bureaus around the country 
the washington post said the wire service plans to eliminate 
oneperson bureaus in green bay wis scranton pa atlantic 
city nj springfield mass and fairfax county va 
capps confirmed that reporting of news in nearby fairfax county 
will now be handled by upis washington bureau but said he would 
not address other details 
he did say that although some of the news bureaus are not now 
being staffed upi has not closed them and retains the option of 
reassigning reporters to them 
we arent reducing any of our coverage in those areas capps 
said we do not consider that there will be any substantive 
change in our reporting from those regions 
he said the changes are part of a longterm strategy aimed at 
trimming personnel costs while sharing news reporting with 
jointventure partners including financial news network a cable 
television network 
upi is owned by infotechnology inc which also owns 47 percent 
of fnn 
our aim is to free up additional resources to differentiate 
upis reports from those of our competitors in ways that cannot be 
easily duplicated capps said 
