<TEXT>
ships going to or coming from iraq will be 
allowed to transit the suez canal despite international sanctions 
against baghdad because of a 102yearold treaty requiring free 
passage the government said tuesday 
under the 1888 constantinople convention governing navigation 
through the canal ships can be denied transit only if they fly the 
flag of a country at war with egypt cairo officials say 
president hosni mubarak cited the convention one week ago when 
he rejected iraqi demands that egypt bar canal passage to us and 
other naval units sent to the persian gulf after iraqs invasion of 
kuwait 
the constantinople convention forbids passage only to ships 
from countries at war with egypt just like you look after your 
interests i look after mine mubarak advised iraq at the time 
the constantinople convention provides in its first article that 
the canal will remain continuously free and open in time of peace 
and also in time of war before all vessels whether commercial or 
military without any discrimination 
article 10 however says provisions decreeing freedom of 
passage shall not conflict with cairos need to defend egypt and 
maintain public security therein 
egypt interprets this as meaning that it has the right to deny 
passage to ships from countries at war with egypt it invoked the 
article in denying transit to israeli ships before the countries 
signed a peace treaty in 1979 
although egypt was not officially a belligerent in world war ii 
british occupation forces in the canal zone closed the waterway to 
ships from nazi germany and italy article 10 apparently was their 
justification 
egypt also normally bans passage of ships propelled by nuclear 
power or carrying nuclear weapons it says the rule is necessary 
for the security of the waterway and the three major population 
centers along its 100mile stretch 
but in recent years cairo has bent the nonuclear rule on 
several occasions to help the united states in emergency situations 
only last week mubarak allowed transit for the nuclearpowered 
us aircraft carrier dwight d eisenhower 
the same exception was granted us warships at least twice 
during the eightyear war between iraq and iran and once in 1986 
in connection with a crisis between the united states and libya 
egypt has had a special relationship with the united states 
since washington brokered its peace treaty with israel cairo has 
received 21 billion annually in us military and economic aid in 
recent years 
the staterun middle east news agency quoted a spokesman for the 
suez canal authority on tuesday as saying that barring iraqi or 
iraqbound ships was neither possible legally nor practical 
those who ask egypt to close the canal to iraqbound ships 
should try to stop these ships at the points of origin not in the 
channel he said 
the spokesman added that even if the waterway were closed to 
iraqbound vessels these ships can simply change their 
destinations to aqaba in jordan instead of to iraq 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

