<TEXT>
truckloads of goods rolled into iraq from 
jordan and iraqibound cargo was unloaded from ships at the 
southern port of aqaba on tuesday despite unordered sanctions 
against baghdad 
king hussein flew to washington on tuesday for talks with 
president bush still refusing to sever what could become iraqs 
economic lifeline the king departed carrying a message to bush 
from iraqi president saddam hussein with whom he met monday 
this indicated hussein is still hoping for a diplomatic solution 
to the crisis caused by iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
husseins refusal to comply with the embargo against iraqi goods 
stems from the impact this would have on jordans fragile economy 
and the expected violent reaction from the largely proiraqi 
jordanians 
foreign ministry undersecretary mutasem belbeisi explained that 
though the un sanctions are mandatory every country whose 
economy can be severely affected can consult with the security 
council to see what measures could be adopted and what sanctions 
could be imposed if any 
western diplomats said the jordanian delegation to the united 
nations was discussing this point in new york 
the imposition of sanctions by jordan would block 40 percent of 
the countrys total exports and raise jordans 16 percent 
unemployment rate by 10 percent to 12 percent jordanian officials 
say 
in addition jordan imports 90 percent of its domestic oil needs 
from iraq 
in israel meanwhile parliamentarian binyamin beneliezer 
demanded tuesday that israel impose a blockade on the jordanian 
port of aqaba where iraqbound supplies were being unloaded 
the southern port is the last opening for goods to reach iraq if 
western vessels completely seal the persian gulf its closure could 
have a severe impact on iraq which is heavily dependent on 
imported foodstuffs and other goods 
associated press photographer martin cleaver said three ships 
docked in the port tuesday and were unloading norwegian newspapers 
reported that police in aqaba ordered a norwegian ship to unload 
corn bound for iraq after the captain stopped deliveries 
cleaver said one of the ships was the tanga from norway he 
could not confirm that police had ordered it to be unloaded 
photographers were unable to approach the tanga which was heavily 
guarded by jordanian troops 
numerous loaded trucks were driving north from aqaba toward 
amman and the iraqi border it was unclear which of the cargoes 
were destined for iraq 
ap photographer yousef allan reported from the ruweishid border 
post on the main highway linking jordan with iraq that the volume 
of heavy trucks and oil tankers traveling both ways had increased 
over the past few days 
officials at the ministry of commerce said oil also continued to 
flow out of iraq through a small pipeline to a point near amman it 
is iraqs last operating oil pipeline since saudi arabia and 
turkey have stopped shipments of iraqi oil transported through 
pipelines on their territory 
jordanian commerce ministry officials said apart from jordanian 
domestic needs the operating pipeline is only used to transport 
50 million worth of oil annually to brazil 
in the persian gulf us and british warships have reportedly 
started checking for shipping bound for iraqi ports western 
diplomats said 
the diplomats said if jordan continued to serve as a transit 
point for iraqi goods it could harm the multinational barricade 
but they said it was unlikely us warships would intervene in the 
gulf of aqaba to stop and check shipping 
king hussein is eager to act as an intermediary in what he has 
described as the impossible job of settling the kuwait crisis 
peacefully through arab mediation he flew to baghdad on monday for 
consultations with the iraqi leader 
the official jordanian news agency petra did not announce his 
trip until after the king returned home tuesday petra said the 
king also talked by telephone to the leaders of yemen tunisia 
sudan and the palestine liberation organization 
