<TEXT>
a searing debate on abortion got 
hotter tuesday when a leading lawmaker insisted west german women 
be barred from taking advantage of east germanys liberal abortion 
law after unification 
abortion tourism to east germany would be unleashed if there 
were no threat of punishment said wolfgang boetsch a 
highranking member of a conservative party that is part of west 
german chancellor helmut kohls coalition government 
sentiments on the issue are so divided that last month the two 
nations postponed deciding on a united germanys abortion statutes 
until an allgerman parliament can take up the matter 
when unity occurs by the end of the year two abortion laws will 
exist in one nation west germanys strict statute and the far 
more lenient one in what is now east germany 
in west germany abortions are allowed only if there is a 
lifethreatening risk to the mother if the pregnancy resulted from 
rape or incest or if birth would create extraordinary social and 
economic hardship 
east german women on the other hand have a fundamental legal 
right to an abortion as long as it occurs within the first 12 
weeks of pregnancy 
east germany with a population of about 16 million last year 
recorded 73000 abortions the figure was 75297 in west germany 
which has a population about four times greater than its eastern 
neighbor 
east germany has insisted that its abortion law be retained 
after unification 
the debate is not only between two nations but also between 
political partners 
the liberal free democrats junior coalition partners in kohls 
government have proposed not to prosecute west german women if 
they choose to travel to what is now east germany for abortions 
after unification 
that idea has enraged the conservative christian social union 
the csu will not abide by such a step boetsch said tuesday 
reversing the states protection for the unborn life is out of 
the question for west germans under any circumstances 
liberal politicians have said that if west germany retains its 
abortion laws a west german woman who had an abortion in an east 
german clinic could face prosecution on her return home 
east german doctors say west german women have already begun 
crossing the border to benefit from east germanys abortion laws 
but east german doctors are not permitted to perform abortions 
on foreigners so far there have been no reports of east german 
doctors violating the law 
parliament president rita suessmuth a top kohl ally has 
ruffled a few conservative feathers by lambasting the west german 
law 
if men were those people who were primarily affected they 
would have made a humane as well as lifeprotecting law long ago 
ms suessmuth said earlier this month 
kohl has stayed clear of the fight but his christian democrats 
have insisted that west germanys abortion law should serve as the 
model for that of a united germany 
ms suessmuth has tried to calm the waters by proposing a 
compromise law for a united germany 
her idea is to meld the intensive consultations required under 
west german law with a womans basic right to an abortion within 
the first trimester 
for many conservatives however that sounds too much like the 
current east german law 
</TEXT>
