about 10000 radical students rallied 
tuesday to demand the immediate unification of the divided korean 
peninsula and vowed to march to the heavily fortified border to 
press for free travel to north korea 
the students gathered at seouls yonsei university said they 
would begin the 35mile march to the border wednesday the 45th 
anniversary of koreas liberation from 35 years of japanese 
colonial rule 
a mass unification rally was scheduled to be held with north 
korea at the border village of panmunjom on wednesday 
before tuesdays rally 79 radical students and dissidents were 
arrested at the sprawling us 8th army headquarters in central 
seoul five of them for ramming a car through the main gate 
the car carrying dissidents and a student radical shouting 
drive out yankees smashed through the military headquarters 
main gate and was stopped about 30 yards inside the facility 
at the rally at yonsei students chanted antiamerican and 
prounification slogans 
lets drive out the yankees who block unification of the 
fatherland they shouted free travel total border opening 
the students are demanding the withdrawal of the 43000 us 
troops stationed in south korea saying their presence hinders 
dialogue with communist north korea on unification 
the students also cut rolls of barbed wire to symbolize hopes 
for an end to the division of the koreas 
student leaders said thousands of people would march to attend 
the unification rally at panmunjom lets go north chanted the 
students 
under a south korean proposal the heavily armed border was to 
have opened for unrestricted travel to north korea for five days 
beginning on monday but both sides failed to agree on procedures 
more than 61000 south koreans applied to visit the north during 
the proposed trial border opening 
the governments unification ministry charged north korea with 
blocking the first proposed free travel between citizens of the 
divided peninsula and urged the north to open its border 
the two koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the 
peninsula in 1945 they fought a threeyear war in the early 1950s 
the border is heavily fortified and there is no mail or other forms 
of regular communication between the two sides 
in north korea 1000 people including koreans from overseas 
and from the south attended ceremonies monday as a prelude to the 
wednesday unification rally the official north korean news agency 
said 
