<TEXT>
after 20 years of contentious litigation over 
sickness and death caused by asbestos a federal judge has taken 
the first step toward a comprehensive solution to the nations 
biggest product liability issue 
but several attorneys are questioning the viability of a single 
plan to resolve tens of thousands of disparate lawsuits seeking 
compensation for lung cancer and other respiratory ailiments caused 
by asbestos 
this litigation is too diffuse to expect that all parties and 
all state courts will consent to a mandatory class action said 
andrew berry a newark nj attorney representing several 
defendants 
in the first move toward a class action lawsuit us district 
judge jack b weinstein on monday ordered hearings to determine 
whether eaglepicher industries inc can settle 65000 pending 
claims in a single case 
weinstein also endorsed combining the manville trust the 
nations largest asbestos claims resolution system with money 
from other defendant companies into a national fund that would 
apportion compensation on the basis of need 
the action followed an unusual joint order friday by 10 federal 
judges from around the country who were frustrated by clogged court 
dockets mounting claims and resolution so slow that many asbestos 
victims die before they are paid 
we have got to pay these people who are entitled to be paid 
and we have to reduce the costs weinstein told a crowded hearing 
in us district court in brooklyn 
weinstein and the nine other federal judges approved a 
threetiered plan for resolving about 90000 lawsuits pending in 
state and federal courts nationwide 
thousands of new lawsuits are filed monthly and legal experts 
estimate hundreds of thousands more cases will be made judges have 
complained that legal costs are siphoning away twothirds of the 
money earmarked for victims 
under the plan weinstein would handle a class action involving 
eaglepicher and up to five more companies that dont have the 
money to fight cases in court or pay present and future claims 
before the case can proceed the court must determine the 
defendants lack resources 
weinsteins case is expected to include the manville trust 
which was formed in 1988 six years after manville corp was forced 
into bankruptcy court protection under the weight of asbestos 
claims 
in part two of the plan thomas d lambros chief judge of 
federal district for northern ohio would attempt to fashion a 
single outofcourt settlement of asbestos claims 
finally us district judge robert parker chief judge of the 
eastern federal district of texas would supervise a classaction 
trial for defendants unwilling or unable to reach settlements 
the movement to reform asbestos litigation gained momentum 
earlier this year when the manville trust announced it had run out 
of money for new claimants and said others wouldnt get money until 
well into the 21st century 
most claimants inhaled asbestos which was used widely for 
insulation while working in shipyards and factories as long ago as 
the 1930s 
judges complain that the same issues are argued over and over 
leading to millions in expenses that might otherwise be used to pay 
victims frivolous claims high fees charged by plaintiffs lawyers 
and a refusal by some defendants to settle also have been 
criticized 
but some attorneys oppose the judges plan saying the issue is 
too complex for a single national solution they predicted a 
breakdown in current settlement talks and timeconsuming court 
appeals that would further delay compensation payments 
if we dont have something available to the victims for the 
next three four five years it takes to establish a national class 
action that would be a disaster to the victim gene locks a 
philadelphia plaintiffs lawyer told weinstein 
in the eaglepicher case weinstein appointed former federal 
judge marvin e frankel to hold hearings on whether the company 
lacks resources so it can qualify for a class action all plaintiffs 
would be required to join 
weinstein who devised a national settlement for vietnam 
warrelated injuries from the defoliant agent orange said hearings 
would open wednesday and promised they would conclude within three 
weeks 
i do not intend that in this court victims wait eight years 
before they get compensation he said this will not be a 
manville reorganization 
eaglepicher based in cincinnati said in court papers it spent 
1197 million on litigation last year and is being named in 2000 
new lawsuits a month 
</TEXT>
