<TEXT>
president bush temporarily turned his 
attention tuesday to work on a budget compromise white house aides 
say the disagreement with congress is becoming more urgent because 
of the mideast crisis 
the president interrupted his maine vacation for two days of 
washington work focused on the huge us effort to punish iraq for 
its invasion of kuwait his first order of business was a meeting 
with advisers on how the crisis could hurt the economy and the 
budget 
bush turned away reporters questions during a photo session at 
the start of his budget meeting the president was joined by his 
chief of staff john sununu and economic adviser michael boskin 
but treasury secretary nicholas brady and budget director richard 
darman did not attend 
the rapid increase in oil prices sparked by the iraqi aggression 
has the potential of tripping up an already weak economy and 
maintaining the huge us force in saudi arabia could add billions 
of dollars to the pentagons annual budget 
brady while not predicting a recession has said the slow 
growth rate of the american economy could fall closer to zero 
as the higher oil prices take full effect 
brady decided not to interrupt his own trip to take part in the 
talks brady a key member of the budget team was in the midwest 
on a twoday campaign swing for republican candidates 
meanwhile marlin fitzwater the white house spokesman said 
we think its even more important that we reach an agreement now 
because there needs to be a unity of purpose in this country not 
only about the conflict in the gulf but also about our spending 
issues and about where the budget is going 
one of the many sticking points in the budget talks which are 
nearly four months old is the level of military spending bush 
requested 303 billion in the fiscal year beginning oct 1 but the 
senate has approved only 289 billion and the house armed services 
committee has endorsed a 283 billion budget 
the white house and congressional conservatives plan to use iraq 
as an argument for a larger military budget the budget talks will 
resume next month when congress returns from its summer recess 
bush has repeatedly expressed his frustration with the talks 
which he initiated in may the two sides are nowhere near an 
agreement despite bushs ending his no new taxes campaign 
pledge 
bush and the republicans have been criticized for suggesting 
higher taxes on alcoholic beverages and a proposal to limit the 
income tax deduction for state and local taxes the democrats 
meanwhile refrained from putting forward any substantive budget 
proposals until after the recess 
the president last week indicated he would step up his 
rhetorical attacks on the democrats but refrained at the time 
because it coincided with his ordering of us troops to the middle 
east 
the goal of the talks is to reduce the federal deficit at least 
50 billion in fiscal 1991 more than has been accomplished in any 
previous budget pact 
even if that were accomplished the spending plan would not meet 
the mandate of the grammrudman budget law that law calls for a 
fiscal 1991 deficit no higher than 64 billion 
according to the latest administration estimates the deficit 
next year will be about 169 billion not counting the 60 billion 
or more needed to continue the bailout of the savings and loan 
industry 
if a budget agreement is reached the legislation would stretch 
out grammrudmans timetable for a balanced budget instead of 
keeping that goal in sight for fiscal 1993 it would be postponed 
until fiscal 1995 or later 
</TEXT>
