<TEXT>
united auto workers union members in flint voted 
tuesday on a proposed contract with general motors corp which has 
been forced to idle several other plants because of labor unrest at 
flint 
the tentative contract was reached monday afternoon the fifth 
day of a strike called over local health and safety matters work 
speedups and the use of outside companies to perform work that 
unionized gm employees could do 
voting at uaw local 659 began tuesday afternoon details of the 
tentative agreement covering about 2800 people werent announced 
before the voting 
the strike at flint has affected other gm plants because of the 
companys reliance on justintime distribution a system that 
delivers parts and components to assembly plants frequently within 
hours of them being installed in new vehicles 
by tuesday the flint strike had shut down five assembly plants 
in michigan ohio and louisiana and portions of some component 
factories resulting in at least 17000 layoffs 
we could certainly see additional impact this week gm 
spokesman john maciarz said tuesday 
tuesdays vote comes as the uaw negotiates national contracts 
with gm ford motor co and chrysler corp to replace agreements 
that expire sept 14 the agreements cover more than 450000 
workers including about 300000 gm employees 
it is unusual for the uaw to begin a local strike during 
national contract talks harley shaiken a labor professor at the 
university of california at san diego said the selective strike 
may be a preview of the unions strategy later on 
analysts also say the flint strike sends a strong indication 
that the uaw will choose to concentrate its national negotiating 
efforts at gm under an arrangement known as pattern bargaining an 
agreement reached at the target company is then presented to the 
other two of the big three automakers for minor customizing before 
being put up for ratification 
if gm werent going to be the target it wouldnt make much 
sense to have this demonstration strike at gm shaiken said 
</TEXT>
